having compassion well up in me

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:45.760
and break my life open in a good
way to the truth of suffering,

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.780
and also the possibility
to transform suffering,

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:53.020
and to realize that
I, as a person who

00:06:53.020 --> 00:06:56.890
was born in the
early 1940s, feel

00:06:56.890 --> 00:07:01.960
that imperative on a daily
basis, what can I do to serve?

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:05.140
What can I do to end suffering?

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:11.170
How to keep myself viable to
meet the truth of suffering

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:12.720
in this world.

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:16.030
So I was so fortunate
to be appointed

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:18.190
as a distinguished
visiting scholar

00:07:18.190 --> 00:07:20.320
at the Library of Congress.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.010
And in the course of
my time at the library,

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:26.530
I began to map out compassion.

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:29.300
Because I realized
that, first of all,

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.490
even though neuroscience and
social psychology, the research

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:36.400
being done in these
areas indicates

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:41.080
the great benefits of compassion
not only to those whom

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.750
are served, but those
who experience it

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:48.070
and to society in general,
but also that compassion

00:07:48.070 --> 00:07:52.810
is in a way, challenged
in our society right now,

00:07:52.810 --> 00:07:56.530
and that it's
difficult for actually

00:07:56.530 --> 00:07:58.720
train people in compassion.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:03.130
Not as an acquired skill, but to
actually create the conditions

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:08.470
where compassion is an emergent
process in our subjectivity.

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:11.440
And so I sat in the
Library of Congress

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:16.520
and began to look at compassion
from many points of view.

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:20.410
And I recognized that
compassion is not

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:25.060
possible without
attentional balance.

00:08:25.060 --> 00:08:26.740
This is really critical.

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:30.160
Our capacity to
actually look deeply

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:34.150
into what is happening
in the present moment

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:40.059
necessitates that we are able
to be very grounded and not

00:08:40.059 --> 00:08:45.820
divided in our attention, not
dispersed in our attention,

00:08:45.820 --> 00:08:48.800
nor distracted.

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:51.920
And just that is the kind
of first base, if you will.

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:55.430
I mean, in a world where
our technology is actually

00:08:55.430 --> 00:09:01.010
designed, interestingly enough,
not necessarily to enhance

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:05.750
focused attention, but
actually to ungrounded us

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:07.580
so that our
consciousness can be,

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:10.100
if you will,
inhabit or colonized

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:13.550
by messages which
aren't necessarily

00:09:13.550 --> 00:09:18.170
benefiting us or others.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:21.100
So the cultivation of
attentional balance

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:25.090
is really critical so that
we have high resolution

00:09:25.090 --> 00:09:29.320
of perception, that we're
able to also sustain

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:32.470
our attention on any
given object, including

00:09:32.470 --> 00:09:38.620
our own subjective experience,
for more than a moment.

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:44.400
It's really hard to put
aside our brain prosthesis.

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:47.070
Because we are,
in a certain way--

00:09:47.070 --> 00:09:54.390
these technological devices
have been so deeply insinuated

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:57.180
into my life, and
also I think the lives

00:09:57.180 --> 00:10:03.990
of most of us in this room and
who are listening to this talk,

00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:08.070
but how do we actually
have the capacity

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:13.590
to allocate our attention to
an individual or to a situation

00:10:13.590 --> 00:10:17.930
without leaving,
abandoning that moment?

00:10:17.930 --> 00:10:21.650
So being grounded and
cultivating attentional balance

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:23.970
is essential.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:26.450
It's also essential to
be pro-social in a way

00:10:26.450 --> 00:10:32.150
to lift out of the negative
narratives that inhabit us.

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:36.510
And prosociality is the
opposite of antisocial.

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:41.180
So it's very powerful
to engage in practices

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:45.830
that actually nourish
beneficial qualities within us.

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:54.040
It's also essential to have a
motivational foundation which

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:58.000
is unselfish, which
is ethical, which

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.300
is about non-harming,
which is engaged

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:06.670
in a process of constantly
inviting us to deconstruct

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:10.720
our fear and open up
to the world in a way

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:16.750
where we're in this beneficial,
non-separate, non-objectifying

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.810
relationship with
so-called others,

00:11:19.810 --> 00:11:24.880
and to actually develop
the capacity to expand

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:28.990
our subjectivity to include
the experience of others

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:32.440
in a way that is healthy.

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:37.000
It's also essential in terms
of compassion to have insight.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.130
Not only insight at the level of
a metacognitive capacity, which

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:44.860
is to stand outside
of our experience,

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:47.590
to see the truth
of impermanence,

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:52.390
to understand that all beings
are really aspiring to be

00:11:52.390 --> 00:11:56.110
happy, even the most deluded
ones and the most politically

00:11:56.110 --> 00:12:01.780
confused ones, but also
that we, on one level,

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:04.660
are very connected
to that person

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:08.110
across from us, the dying
person, the prisoner,

00:12:08.110 --> 00:12:11.920
our child, our
teacher, our boss,

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:15.080
but also we are not that person.

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:18.910
So the distinction
between self and other,

00:12:18.910 --> 00:12:21.520
understanding that
distinction is

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:26.710
critical in terms of us
being able to regulate

00:12:26.710 --> 00:12:29.800
our experience of
resonance with whatever is

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:31.690
arising in the present moment.

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:37.420
So the map grew.

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:41.710
And it, I think, has
been of help to others.

00:12:41.710 --> 00:12:45.730
People in the neuroscience
and social psychology research

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:49.480
world, but also it's been very
helpful in terms of developing

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:51.250
training protocols.

00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:55.480
And I developed a very
simple one called GRACE,

00:12:55.480 --> 00:13:01.120
which I can just share briefly
here, which many clinicians--

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.530
and actually, there's a National
GRACE Organization in Japan

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:05.680
now--

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:11.680
many clinicians use, and I'll
just give you the shortcut.

00:13:11.680 --> 00:13:18.300
The G of GRACE is
gathering your attention.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:21.830
How do you really get
grounded in this moment?

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:28.070
The R of GRACE is
recalling your intention.

00:13:28.070 --> 00:13:32.760
What is our motivation
for any given action?

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:36.150
The A of GRACE is
attuning to oneself,

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:41.550
to one's own subjectivity,
to our somatic experience,

00:13:41.550 --> 00:13:46.050
to our emotional experience,
and to the actual cognitive

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:51.420
experience that we have
before we attune to others.

00:13:51.420 --> 00:13:54.500
So once you understand
the protocol,

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:56.940
it's a lived in
act of compassion.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:58.860
It happens in an instant.

00:13:58.860 --> 00:14:03.400
You can really assay your
subjectivity physically,

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:07.590
emotionally, and cognitively
before you actually

00:14:07.590 --> 00:14:11.700
include the experience of
others into your subjectivity,

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:13.860
engage in empathy.

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.590
So this is other attunement.

00:14:16.590 --> 00:14:22.280
Attuning first to yourself,
and then attuning to the other.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:26.840
And then from that base,
the C of GRACE, which is

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:31.000
consider what will really serve.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.890
And then the E of GRACE
is engage and end.

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:39.080
Ending is really important.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:44.020
So this is a tool that
many clinicians are using

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:45.520
and educators at this time.

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:49.120
And actually, it's just great if
you're a parent or a colleague.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:54.280
It just has a way of grounding
you, remembering who you really

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:56.830
are, attuning to
your own situation

00:14:56.830 --> 00:14:58.960
before you include
others into it

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:02.570
and getting grounded,
and so forth.

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:07.490
So in the process of
working on this project,

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:15.840
I began to consider how
the absence of compassion,

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.510
the absence of
attentional balance,

00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:21.630
the absence of
emotional balance,

00:15:21.630 --> 00:15:26.400
the lack of capacity to tune
into one's own subjectivity,

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:31.320
the inability to be in
resonance with others, and also

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:39.090
how fast the reaction time often
is at great cost in the end,

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:43.920
or how fear inhibits
us from acting.

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:47.480
And over many decades,
literally thousands

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:50.030
of people in end
of life care field,

00:15:50.030 --> 00:15:53.660
educators, people involved in
corporations in the business

00:15:53.660 --> 00:16:00.050
world, parents, practitioners
have shared with me

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:02.870
the challenges that
they've experienced

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:04.820
in meeting suffering.

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:08.150
And by the way, I'm
not just speaking

00:16:08.150 --> 00:16:11.630
about the kind of dramatic
suffering that, for example,

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:14.790
I in end of life care
field would encounter.

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:17.450
I'm speaking about the kind
of day-to-day suffering

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:22.010
that you would encounter as
you meet with colleagues who

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:26.750
are super upregulated or
very depressed or angry,

00:16:26.750 --> 00:16:31.070
or with a parent
whose child has died

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:34.870
or whose child is extremely ill.

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:37.390
And I began to
realize, actually,

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:40.990
I suffered in the same way
as those who were sharing

00:16:40.990 --> 00:16:43.630
their difficulties with me.

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:47.470
And I located, if you
will, five geographies

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:51.940
in the ecosystem
of our subjectivity

00:16:51.940 --> 00:16:55.960
that are really
extraordinary capacities

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:00.610
within our human
experience, without which

00:17:00.610 --> 00:17:05.800
we would be deeply
challenged as individuals,

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:08.290
and as a social body,
and as a body that

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:12.250
lives within the
environment on this Earth.

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:18.310
And those five capacities were--
interestingly enough for me--

00:17:18.310 --> 00:17:26.170
capacities which had a deeply
challenged shadow aspect.

00:17:26.170 --> 00:17:29.030
And they're capacities
which we value,

00:17:29.030 --> 00:17:33.700
but we often don't realize
that they can make us ill.

00:17:33.700 --> 00:17:36.640
They can be great hindrances.

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.340
And this is actually what
I outlined in the book.

00:17:39.340 --> 00:17:41.770
I call them edge states.

00:17:41.770 --> 00:17:49.090
Because they are ecologies that
include healthy manifestations,

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:54.460
but also they're ecologies
that include unhealthy aspects.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:59.640
And it's very important for us
to realize this vision of edge

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:03.520
states that falling
over the edge

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:06.880
isn't necessarily a
terminal condition,

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:10.210
that actually climbing back
onto the high edge of any

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:15.470
of these qualities produces
potentially a lot of strength,

00:18:15.470 --> 00:18:17.390
a lot of character.

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:20.020
But it's important to
also have the ability

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:23.470
to stand on the high edge
of any of these capacities,

00:18:23.470 --> 00:18:28.870
to see the entire landscape
of the toxic aspect,

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:33.400
or aspects in the
challenged aspects.

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:39.390
So the first edge that I
looked at was altruism.

00:18:39.390 --> 00:18:42.300
Nicholas Winton
was a great example

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:47.940
of an altruist, someone
who felt the imperative.

00:18:47.940 --> 00:18:51.840
Just as [? Chante ?] Davis
says, you step on a thorn,

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:56.130
and the hand doesn't sort
of ask the foot permission

00:18:56.130 --> 00:18:57.960
to remove the thorn.

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:02.310
The hand goes immediately to the
foot and pulls the thorn out.

00:19:02.310 --> 00:19:05.400
It's this kind of
seamlessness of response.

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:14.040
I read in "The New York Times"
a very interesting story

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:17.370
about a man called
Wesley Autrey.

00:19:17.370 --> 00:19:20.610
And Wesley Autrey was
an Afro-American man

00:19:20.610 --> 00:19:24.300
who was standing on a
subway platform with his two

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:26.160
daughters, and
there were probably

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:31.650
100 people on that subway
platform along with him.

00:19:31.650 --> 00:19:35.760
And all of a sudden, a young
white guy had a seizure

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:39.870
and fell into the subway tracks.

00:19:39.870 --> 00:19:43.260
And as this young guy
was having the seizure,

00:19:43.260 --> 00:19:49.570
Wesley Autrey saw the
oncoming subway, jumped off

00:19:49.570 --> 00:19:52.980
of the subway platform, leaving
his two little girls who

00:19:52.980 --> 00:19:57.390
were standing right beside him
there on the subway platform,

00:19:57.390 --> 00:20:03.420
got on top of this young
guy, and he realized

00:20:03.420 --> 00:20:07.490
that if he wasn't able
to hold this guy down,

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:10.140
and he certainly
wasn't able to drag him

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:15.930
off the tracks in time, that he
and this young guy would die.

00:20:15.930 --> 00:20:19.920
And he held this seizing
young man down on the tracks,

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:25.800
and the subway passed over his
head, grazing his knit cap.

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:30.150
And he was hailed as
an incredible hero,

00:20:30.150 --> 00:20:34.230
and it was a decision
that was like that.

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:38.250
He didn't say, well,
my military background

00:20:38.250 --> 00:20:40.470
is giving me the
capacity to do this,

00:20:40.470 --> 00:20:43.840
and I'll be a big deal
in "The New York Times"

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:46.540
and lauded as a hero.

00:20:46.540 --> 00:20:48.240
He just went for it.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:54.760
Now the shadow
side of altruism is

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:58.770
called pathological altruism.

00:20:58.770 --> 00:21:01.140
And pathological
altruism is that we

00:21:01.140 --> 00:21:06.270
engage in an action of service
toward others, or another,

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:10.800
or toward an institution,
or toward a country which

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:16.080
endeavors to be beneficial,
but that that act of altruism

00:21:16.080 --> 00:21:20.580
actually causes harm to
ourselves, to those who we're

00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:23.970
endeavoring to serve,
to the institution

00:21:23.970 --> 00:21:28.530
that we perhaps are part of,
to the institution that we're

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:31.750
trying to serve, or to the
country that we're serving.

00:21:31.750 --> 00:21:34.800
So a good example of
pathological altruism

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:37.920
is what happened in Haiti.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:42.810
Very interesting, this notion
of pathological altruism.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:45.630
And also what is
so fascinating is

00:21:45.630 --> 00:21:51.960
how tenuous that line is between
altruism and pathological

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:53.370
altruism.

00:21:53.370 --> 00:21:57.210
Because if you take the
example of Wesley Autrey,

00:21:57.210 --> 00:22:07.280
a very selfless, dramatic act,
unprecedented in a certain way,

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:10.910
no preconception, just a leap.

00:22:10.910 --> 00:22:14.660
If the train, the
subway had killed him

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:19.250
and also killed
Autrey, he probably

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:23.670
would have been deemed
a pathological altruist.

00:22:23.670 --> 00:22:25.920
So it's very fascinating.

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:33.150
We just-- the line is
fragile, to say the least.

00:22:33.150 --> 00:22:35.730
There's a big grey area.

00:22:35.730 --> 00:22:41.070
But it's also a very
important quality for us

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:42.990
to examine deeply.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:46.860
Because just as the
case of Nicholas Winton

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:50.760
and of Wesley Autrey,
both of these people

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:54.960
acted not selfishly,
but from a perspective

00:22:54.960 --> 00:22:58.440
of complete unselfishness
in this very

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:00.960
seamless, unfiltered way.

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:04.350
And this is, if you will,
one of the qualities

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:06.120
or aspects of altruism.

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:18.100
The second quality
that I jumped into,

00:23:18.100 --> 00:23:21.920
I heard so much about
it over the years.

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:26.260
In fact, interestingly enough,
I was in a conversation

00:23:26.260 --> 00:23:30.790
a few days ago with
a young Indian man

00:23:30.790 --> 00:23:36.520
who's a Zen practitioner who
is a specialist at AI who

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:39.460
said that he can hardly
turn on the news he's

00:23:39.460 --> 00:23:48.330
so overwhelmed in
accessing the news today.

00:23:48.330 --> 00:23:51.100
And he had my book and
asked me to sign it.

00:23:51.100 --> 00:23:54.450
He said, you know, I'm
beginning to understand

00:23:54.450 --> 00:23:59.040
something about empathy
from what you've written.

00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:05.610
So empathy is that experience of
somatic emotional or affective

00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:10.470
resonance, as well as cognitive
resonance with another.

00:24:10.470 --> 00:24:13.470
We can be somatically
attuned, for example,

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:17.550
and not being necessarily
in resonance emotionally

00:24:17.550 --> 00:24:20.340
and cognitively, but
we can have all three

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:23.760
of our perceiving
mechanisms engaged,

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:26.730
our sensing mechanisms engaged.

00:24:26.730 --> 00:24:29.940
It's that experience where
our subjectivity begins

00:24:29.940 --> 00:24:33.570
to drop away in terms
of the small self,

00:24:33.570 --> 00:24:38.340
and we practice a kind
of increasing inclusivity

00:24:38.340 --> 00:24:43.050
which is really important from
the point of view of meditation

00:24:43.050 --> 00:24:43.590
practice.

00:24:43.590 --> 00:24:48.460
Because fundamentally,
our realization

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:51.370
in meditation practice,
the sort of sign of it

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:54.460
is that we recognize
that we're deeply

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:59.790
interconnected with
all beings and things.

00:24:59.790 --> 00:25:04.830
But when we're so connected
with all beings and things, when

00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:10.560
we, for example, over-identify
with the dying patient,

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:14.820
or with our boss who
might be angry at us,

00:25:14.820 --> 00:25:19.500
or our child who is acting
out, or a colleague who

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:22.290
has experienced
profound loss, it

00:25:22.290 --> 00:25:25.260
becomes a very
difficult situation

00:25:25.260 --> 00:25:29.040
where we can experience
secondary trauma.

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:34.380
And I have to say, that
young guy in the AI world

00:25:34.380 --> 00:25:37.770
that I talked to, or who
talked to me a few days ago,

00:25:37.770 --> 00:25:44.540
I have to titrate my
consumption of news too.

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:50.360
Because I notice if I
take in too much bad news,

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:53.000
I begin to shut down.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.550
I begin to go numb.

00:25:55.550 --> 00:25:59.540
But it's very
important to understand

00:25:59.540 --> 00:26:06.200
where your boundaries are,
what serves your awakening.

00:26:06.200 --> 00:26:14.350
When one over-identifies
with, for example,

00:26:14.350 --> 00:26:20.770
the Fuhrer in Nazi
Germany, where you--

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:24.220
it's not just with the
ordinary kind of suffering,

00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:29.920
but it's also, for example, in
cults, or views, or even inside

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.980
of a corporate
system, and you begin

00:26:32.980 --> 00:26:38.110
to lose your own moral compass,
the principles by which you're

00:26:38.110 --> 00:26:39.190
living.

00:26:39.190 --> 00:26:42.430
Even a corporation
can be a kind of cult,

00:26:42.430 --> 00:26:49.490
if you will, where
diversity is not condoned,

00:26:49.490 --> 00:26:53.670
where it's looked on as
a threat to identity.

00:26:53.670 --> 00:26:56.720
That's why I'm so glad to see so
many different colors of seats

00:26:56.720 --> 00:27:01.490
here, and also just a feeling
of diversity in this community

00:27:01.490 --> 00:27:03.240
here.

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:06.410
But when that
experience of arousal

00:27:06.410 --> 00:27:10.880
happens in connection with
the experience of others,

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:13.100
and if that
experience of arousal

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:18.080
is not regulated, either from a
bottom up perspective, that is,

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:22.250
the perspective of a kind
of natural regulation

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:26.000
that happens to keep us
from moving into overwhelm,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:32.390
or a top down regulation where
we can, sensing into our body,

00:27:32.390 --> 00:27:34.790
recognize the signals
that are coming up

00:27:34.790 --> 00:27:38.180
from this amazing
organism that is

00:27:38.180 --> 00:27:43.340
a repository of an enormous
amount of information

00:27:43.340 --> 00:27:48.410
that we're often dissociated
from as we are attending

00:27:48.410 --> 00:27:52.170
to our digital
device, for example,

00:27:52.170 --> 00:27:56.880
where we lose touch
with the messages coming

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:01.820
from the body telling us, oh,
I have a lot of fear coming up.

00:28:01.820 --> 00:28:04.220
I can feel it in my diaphragm.

00:28:04.220 --> 00:28:06.800
I can feel the
tension in my legs.

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:09.930
I know I'm violating
my integrity.

00:28:09.930 --> 00:28:13.160
I feel my guts are squeezing.

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:15.170
My heart rate is increasing.

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:19.940
Or I'm witnessing suffering,
and I have a vasovagal moment

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:22.460
where I'm about to pass out.

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:25.050
If we're not able to
regulate ourselves,

00:28:25.050 --> 00:28:27.800
we can be traumatized.

00:28:27.800 --> 00:28:32.330
We can move into the
experience of distress.

00:28:32.330 --> 00:28:37.410
And this is one of the reasons
why practice is so important.

00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:40.560
It's not about
disassociating from the body.

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:44.000
It's actually being in this
experience of embodiment

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.350
so that we can sense into
our visceral processes

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:51.410
and receive the information
that's coming up

00:28:51.410 --> 00:28:55.070
from the body about
what kind of response

00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:59.210
we're experiencing in relation
to external events, or even

00:28:59.210 --> 00:29:00.460
internal processes.

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:07.200
So this is called
empathic distress

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:09.940
and empathic over-arousal.

00:29:09.940 --> 00:29:12.015
It is the shadow
side of empathy.

00:29:14.530 --> 00:29:22.000
The next ecology that I
looked at with great interest

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.870
was that of integrity.

00:29:25.870 --> 00:29:29.600
We can ask what we
mean by integrity,

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:32.120
and from my point
of view, integrity

00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:36.570
has to do with nonviolence
and non-harming.

00:29:36.570 --> 00:29:41.460
How do we actually nurture
integrity in a world

00:29:41.460 --> 00:29:47.520
where there is so much
violence, such deep dissociation

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:52.440
from this planet Earth,
where war is the norm,

00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:54.660
and where violence
is being fed to us

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:57.920
through the media constantly?

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:01.040
And I looked at the
shadow side of integrity

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:05.900
and saw there are basically
four valences to what I've

00:30:05.900 --> 00:30:08.600
termed moral suffering.

00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:10.850
And by moral
suffering, I'm talking

00:30:10.850 --> 00:30:15.470
about that feeling of
trespass that many of us

00:30:15.470 --> 00:30:19.160
experience when we engage
directly or indirectly

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:22.210
in behaviors that are harmful.

00:30:22.210 --> 00:30:26.300
And they include four
different expressions.

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:32.190
And one of those expressions
is called moral distress.

00:30:32.190 --> 00:30:36.210
And it's when you see a
situation where there is

00:30:36.210 --> 00:30:42.810
a violation of values, of
principles, of beneficence,

00:30:42.810 --> 00:30:48.650
you see a way through, but
you cannot actualize it.

00:30:48.650 --> 00:30:50.840
Moral distress.

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:55.520
Moral injury, which
is well-documented

00:30:55.520 --> 00:31:02.910
in the military, but also, we
see it in education, medicine,

00:31:02.910 --> 00:31:06.150
and in big corporations as well.

00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:09.620
And this is when you
are in a system that

00:31:09.620 --> 00:31:12.770
is causing harm to others.

00:31:12.770 --> 00:31:16.430
You either are part of it
or you're witnessing it,

00:31:16.430 --> 00:31:20.510
and you feel shame
and self-blame.

00:31:20.510 --> 00:31:21.440
Moral injury.

00:31:24.340 --> 00:31:29.690
The third aspect is
called moral outrage.

00:31:29.690 --> 00:31:34.070
And I have a bit more of a
predisposition toward that.

00:31:34.070 --> 00:31:36.290
I have some toward
more moral injury

00:31:36.290 --> 00:31:39.110
and some toward
moral distress too,

00:31:39.110 --> 00:31:41.900
but it is the sense
of anger and disgust

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:47.330
that arises when you perceive,
external to yourself,

00:31:47.330 --> 00:31:49.620
acts that harm.

00:31:49.620 --> 00:31:52.080
And it can be chronic.

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:56.100
There are many of my
friends and I kind of--

00:31:56.100 --> 00:31:57.600
I don't think I'm
chronically in it,

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:00.860
but I kind of know
it pretty well.

00:32:00.860 --> 00:32:05.120
The sense, just looking at
our political landscape,

00:32:05.120 --> 00:32:10.010
feeling moral outrage, or
looking at war in the world

00:32:10.010 --> 00:32:13.010
and feeling a sense
of moral outrage.

00:32:13.010 --> 00:32:15.330
And the shaming and
blaming, of course,

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:20.890
is expressed outwardly
toward others.

00:32:20.890 --> 00:32:28.190
And then the fourth one
is called moral apathy.

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:31.910
And actually, I didn't even
think about moral apathy

00:32:31.910 --> 00:32:36.140
at all, because I'm in
the bubble of my world,

00:32:36.140 --> 00:32:40.950
until I went to see
"I'm not your Negro",

00:32:40.950 --> 00:32:44.610
And I heard the
term moral apathy,

00:32:44.610 --> 00:32:47.610
and I was like, that's it.

00:32:47.610 --> 00:32:55.350
It is when we live in a bubble
of privilege, or of addiction,

00:32:55.350 --> 00:33:00.800
or denial, or fear
that disallows us

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:04.940
from seeing what really
is going on at the systems

00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:09.850
level in our surround.

00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:12.290
Where we have turned
away, if you will,

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:15.590
from the truth of suffering.

00:33:15.590 --> 00:33:18.960
And I know recently, I was
flying internationally,

00:33:18.960 --> 00:33:22.180
and I had this--

00:33:22.180 --> 00:33:28.060
going through the airport
as a privileged Anglo-Saxon

00:33:28.060 --> 00:33:33.810
Protestant Zen person,
and I saw a woman

00:33:33.810 --> 00:33:37.950
in a burqa coming up beside me.

00:33:37.950 --> 00:33:44.590
And I realized she was in a
much more vulnerable position

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:50.590
than I. And I had this
flash about the privilege

00:33:50.590 --> 00:33:55.840
that I enjoy, and also
of compassion for anyone

00:33:55.840 --> 00:34:00.580
whose identity puts them
on the margin of what

00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:05.130
appears to be socially
and psychologically safe.

00:34:05.130 --> 00:34:08.580
And I remember just
I did this thing--

00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:10.290
I mean, she probably
thought I was crazy.

00:34:10.290 --> 00:34:14.580
But I put my hands together and
made a little bow to her just

00:34:14.580 --> 00:34:21.489
to make that connection
in that moment.

00:34:21.489 --> 00:34:23.710
Integrity.

00:34:23.710 --> 00:34:27.580
The fourth edge state
that I've written about

00:34:27.580 --> 00:34:30.730
is in relation to respect.

00:34:30.730 --> 00:34:37.210
And it's when we hold really,
all beings in equal regard.

00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:42.240
And I had when I was working in
the penitentiary of New Mexico

00:34:42.240 --> 00:34:47.980
a really deep experience of
walking into a system that

00:34:47.980 --> 00:34:51.670
is characterized by
a lot of violence,

00:34:51.670 --> 00:34:56.020
of working inside as a
volunteer for six years

00:34:56.020 --> 00:35:00.720
with men in maximum
security in death row.

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:03.840
And it was such a
wake up call for me,

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:08.220
because I walked into that
system with a lot of judgments.

00:35:08.220 --> 00:35:13.170
And actually, what I
learned from being inside

00:35:13.170 --> 00:35:17.070
was these are human beings.

00:35:17.070 --> 00:35:20.740
They've caused immense
suffering to others.

00:35:20.740 --> 00:35:23.940
It was not a matter
of me being in a kind

00:35:23.940 --> 00:35:28.320
of romantic
atmosphere internally

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:33.450
about the truth of suffering
in a very violent, rage-filled

00:35:33.450 --> 00:35:37.710
penitentiary system, but it
was developing the capacity

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:43.390
to see the truth of a
particular kind of suffering.

00:35:43.390 --> 00:35:47.920
Per individual, every individual
had a different narrative.

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:52.520
Some of the narratives were
really horrifying to consider.

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:54.940
But at the same time,
to recognize that

00:35:54.940 --> 00:35:58.750
beneath the narrative,
beneath the actions

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:02.320
of any one of those
individuals was a human being.

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:06.310
No matter that they
had raped and killed

00:36:06.310 --> 00:36:09.940
children, or their
parents, or strangers,

00:36:09.940 --> 00:36:13.070
there was a human
being under there.

00:36:13.070 --> 00:36:15.370
And part of the
work was to actually

00:36:15.370 --> 00:36:19.090
hold the truth of the
narrative, as constructed

00:36:19.090 --> 00:36:23.560
as it was, and also the truth
that maybe not this lifetime,

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:26.200
but maybe in some
lifetime, this one will be

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:29.170
liberated from their delusion.

00:36:29.170 --> 00:36:33.970
So I learned so much
working inside that system.

00:36:33.970 --> 00:36:37.750
But that system, our
corrections system,

00:36:37.750 --> 00:36:41.830
is actually a kind
of ground engendering

00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:45.080
phenomenal disrespect.

00:36:45.080 --> 00:36:48.610
And I began also to look
at respect and disrespect

00:36:48.610 --> 00:36:52.690
in medicine, particularly
after a student of mine,

00:36:52.690 --> 00:36:56.860
who was a nurse, did a thesis
at our chaplaincy training

00:36:56.860 --> 00:37:01.120
on what is termed
horizontal hostility.

00:37:01.120 --> 00:37:06.710
And this is behaviors of
disrespect between peers.

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:11.740
Bullying, disparagement,
third party communication,

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:14.590
dissing and so forth.

00:37:14.590 --> 00:37:21.120
And what she brought my
attention to is that 15% to 20%

00:37:21.120 --> 00:37:25.650
of nurses actually leave the
nursing profession because

00:37:25.650 --> 00:37:30.810
of having been bullied, and
just being unable to sustain it.

00:37:30.810 --> 00:37:35.070
And it's interesting to
look at that in relation,

00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:40.240
for example, to the
culture here at Google,

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:44.480
or the culture in any
corporation around gender,

00:37:44.480 --> 00:37:49.580
for example, around
race, ethnicity,

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:53.720
around religion
view, around height.

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:57.800
I can say as a short
woman, sometimes

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:02.810
I'm actually treated more
like a pet than a person.

00:38:02.810 --> 00:38:06.970
And you can imagine that does--

00:38:06.970 --> 00:38:08.420
that's right, moral outrage.

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:11.360
That does nothing for
me or the other person.

00:38:11.360 --> 00:38:16.130
I try to do my best to
help set things straight,

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:18.920
needless to say.

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:22.040
So horizontal
hostility is actually

00:38:22.040 --> 00:38:25.060
rampant in our culture.

00:38:25.060 --> 00:38:29.950
And it's a complement,
so to speak,

00:38:29.950 --> 00:38:35.290
in the world of verticality is
called vertical violence, which

00:38:35.290 --> 00:38:37.660
can happen in a top down way.

00:38:37.660 --> 00:38:40.210
And certainly, we
see it in terms of--

00:38:40.210 --> 00:38:43.030
well, you see horizontal
hostility, for example,

00:38:43.030 --> 00:38:47.620
in the political arena, of how
candidates treat each other

00:38:47.620 --> 00:38:49.510
and speak about
each other, and it's

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:54.220
kind of horrifying for
our children to witness.

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:56.200
But you also see
vertical violence

00:38:56.200 --> 00:39:02.530
in terms of the disrespect
that our politicians

00:39:02.530 --> 00:39:07.870
engage in in relation to people
who are differently abled,

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:12.250
or from other cultures,
other societies.

00:39:12.250 --> 00:39:17.440
There is also a bottom
up vertical violence,

00:39:17.440 --> 00:39:20.140
where people who are
less empowered, less

00:39:20.140 --> 00:39:25.510
acknowledged actually
manifest dramatic disrespect

00:39:25.510 --> 00:39:29.180
toward those who are in power.

00:39:29.180 --> 00:39:32.430
So part of the work
is how do we actually

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:37.080
come into this
experience of recognizing

00:39:37.080 --> 00:39:42.090
our fundamental humanity in
relation to others, all others?

00:39:42.090 --> 00:39:47.040
And respect is something that
is about holding all beings

00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:50.610
and things, including all
species on this Earth,

00:39:50.610 --> 00:39:54.550
in equal regard.

00:39:54.550 --> 00:40:02.780
The final piece that I looked
at was burnout and engagement.

00:40:02.780 --> 00:40:08.090
Our capacity to
engage in a vocation,

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:13.530
in work that is meaningful
is really important.

00:40:13.530 --> 00:40:19.970
Our workplaces also have to
be nontoxic in order for us

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:21.770
to survive.

00:40:21.770 --> 00:40:24.230
And we also have to
have good agreements

00:40:24.230 --> 00:40:27.650
with our places of employment.

00:40:27.650 --> 00:40:29.060
Engagement is essential.

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:32.870
A sense of enthusiasm, of
dedication, having work

00:40:32.870 --> 00:40:36.140
that is about benefiting
others and working

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:39.780
in healthy environments
is really essential.

00:40:39.780 --> 00:40:42.470
And by the same
token, what happens

00:40:42.470 --> 00:40:48.410
when those aspects are not
part of our work environment.

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:50.780
The outcome, of
course, is burnout.

00:40:50.780 --> 00:40:53.840
We become completely exhausted.

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:57.950
So I do a big thing on burnout.

00:40:57.950 --> 00:41:01.280
So we can look at our experience
in an interesting way,

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:04.010
because whether we're
in the human rights

00:41:04.010 --> 00:41:07.490
field or the health
care field, all of us

00:41:07.490 --> 00:41:12.140
have, in one way or another,
fallen over the edge.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:17.570
And one of the principles
operating in this work

00:41:17.570 --> 00:41:22.260
is how powerful it is not
just to fall over the edge

00:41:22.260 --> 00:41:27.840
and to encounter failure
and to be traumatized,

00:41:27.840 --> 00:41:33.380
but also the repair process that
actually builds character, that

00:41:33.380 --> 00:41:37.160
enhances our
resilience, that deepens

00:41:37.160 --> 00:41:41.510
our sense of flourishing,
that gives us deeper meaning.

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.250
It's really important.

00:41:43.250 --> 00:41:49.340
And I said at another Silicon
Valley company yesterday,

00:41:49.340 --> 00:41:54.920
it is important to
actually include failure

00:41:54.920 --> 00:41:58.460
into the equation of success.

00:41:58.460 --> 00:42:01.910
We know from the point
of view of living systems

00:42:01.910 --> 00:42:08.390
that systems that break down
and learn from the breakdown

00:42:08.390 --> 00:42:13.550
can reorganize themselves at
a much higher and more robust

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:15.050
level.

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:18.650
And robust is the
key here, robustness.

00:42:18.650 --> 00:42:22.220
Our capacity to
actually encounter

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:27.920
incredible difficulties,
loss, sorrow, failure,

00:42:27.920 --> 00:42:32.810
and to use that
experience as a way

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:38.690
to engender, not only humility,
but to engender wisdom.

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:45.960
The capacity to see deeply
into who we really are.

00:42:45.960 --> 00:42:49.670
So I ask myself, what
was the kind of pivot?

00:42:49.670 --> 00:42:54.680
How do we actually work the
edge of these edge states?

00:42:54.680 --> 00:43:00.290
And I realized that the most
important thing that we can do

00:43:00.290 --> 00:43:04.730
is to actualize compassion,
because compassion gives you

00:43:04.730 --> 00:43:09.530
the attentional balance,
emotional balance, and insight

00:43:09.530 --> 00:43:14.090
that allows you to transform
even the experiences that have

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:19.280
caused us distress, have
caused us the most suffering

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:22.710
into qualities of strength.

00:43:22.710 --> 00:43:25.590
So what I'd love
to do in finishing

00:43:25.590 --> 00:43:29.940
this short presentation
is to open up

00:43:29.940 --> 00:43:32.100
for questions or comments.

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:37.890
I'd be really happy to hear
more from you than from me.

00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:40.050
