00:48:37.730 --> 00:48:38.920
Yeah?

00:48:38.920 --> 00:48:39.830
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:44.300
I've read a little bit recently
about compassion fatigue, which

00:48:44.300 --> 00:48:47.210
is something professional
caregivers spend

00:48:47.210 --> 00:48:49.580
so much of their
energy helping others

00:48:49.580 --> 00:48:53.430
that they find that they don't
have any left for friends

00:48:53.430 --> 00:48:53.930
and family.

00:48:53.930 --> 00:48:56.580
And in my last
relationship, I was

00:48:56.580 --> 00:49:00.180
very much on the receiving end
of that, which was very hard.

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:04.590
I'm a nurse who worked in
Nepal after the earthquake.

00:49:04.590 --> 00:49:07.620
JOAN HALIFAX: A nurse who worked
in Nepal after the earthquake.

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:08.120
Daniel.

00:49:08.120 --> 00:49:11.290
The question Daniel asked
is very interesting.

00:49:11.290 --> 00:49:16.110
It was about the
challenges associated

00:49:16.110 --> 00:49:18.850
with so-called
compassion fatigue.

00:49:18.850 --> 00:49:22.470
So I think Richie
Davidson, [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:24.540
and I agree on many
things, including

00:49:24.540 --> 00:49:27.930
the fact there's no such
thing as compassion fatigue.

00:49:27.930 --> 00:49:28.780
Yeah.

00:49:28.780 --> 00:49:31.770
What actually one
is experiencing

00:49:31.770 --> 00:49:34.390
is empathic distress.

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:38.880
And it's created a problem
inside health systems

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:42.510
where the word or the
term compassion fatigue

00:49:42.510 --> 00:49:46.710
has been used, and
so it's conduced

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:50.130
to a situation of suspicion
toward the experience

00:49:50.130 --> 00:49:51.810
of compassion.

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:54.570
So when we're in this
kind of resonance

00:49:54.570 --> 00:50:00.570
with others and over-identified,
we can be easily overwhelmed.

00:50:00.570 --> 00:50:03.030
But compassion as
I described it,

00:50:03.030 --> 00:50:08.130
as composing or comprised
of attentional balance,

00:50:08.130 --> 00:50:11.370
emotional balance,
inside an embodiment,

00:50:11.370 --> 00:50:13.530
it does not fatigue you.

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:18.120
And what the fascinating
research done by Davidson,

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:20.910
and Lutz, and Chuck
Raison, and Tanya Singer,

00:50:20.910 --> 00:50:23.490
and a number of
other neuroscientists

00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:26.340
and social psychologists
have given us

00:50:26.340 --> 00:50:30.870
a good view that compassion
actually enhances

00:50:30.870 --> 00:50:37.680
resilience, enhances immune
response, enhances longevity.

00:50:37.680 --> 00:50:39.780
It's morally elevating.

00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:43.440
And when we don't
respond compassionately,

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:46.230
we feel morally compromised.

00:50:46.230 --> 00:50:49.360
As well, it's contagious.

00:50:49.360 --> 00:50:53.160
So when you see someone
out in the world doing

00:50:53.160 --> 00:50:57.930
a good thing, like for example,
Nicholas Winton or Wesley

00:50:57.930 --> 00:51:03.180
Autrey, you have this feeling
of I want to be like that.

00:51:03.180 --> 00:51:08.310
It's this natural arising of
this experience of the value

00:51:08.310 --> 00:51:10.900
of being in service to others.

00:51:10.900 --> 00:51:15.420
So I would love for you
to just delete that term

00:51:15.420 --> 00:51:20.430
from your psyche
and to actually use

00:51:20.430 --> 00:51:25.150
another term which is called
empathic distress in its place.

00:51:25.150 --> 00:51:28.140
I have experienced
empathic distress.

00:51:28.140 --> 00:51:32.100
In the introduction--
but compassion fatigue,

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:36.000
it's not compassion that
we're talking about.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.490
It really has to do with
empathy and burnout.

00:51:39.490 --> 00:51:42.460
And so in the introduction
to the empathy chapter,

00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:45.180
I talk about being in this
small clinic in Nepal,

00:51:45.180 --> 00:51:51.060
and a very haggard man walked
into the clinic clutching

00:51:51.060 --> 00:51:54.330
a little bundle in his arms.

00:51:54.330 --> 00:51:58.350
And one of our clinicians
walked up, helped the man unwrap

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:03.000
the bundle, and it was a little
girl who was horribly burned.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:10.070
And so we took her into one of
the clinics rooms and began,

00:52:10.070 --> 00:52:15.030
the clinicians, the Nepali
nurses and doctors and our team

00:52:15.030 --> 00:52:17.460
began to debride her
wounds, but we didn't

00:52:17.460 --> 00:52:20.130
have pediatric anesthesia.

00:52:20.130 --> 00:52:24.270
And I was in such
resonance with this child

00:52:24.270 --> 00:52:27.840
that I had a vasovagal response.

00:52:27.840 --> 00:52:29.320
I almost passed out.

00:52:29.320 --> 00:52:31.770
I thought I was going to
throw up on the floor.

00:52:31.770 --> 00:52:35.890
And I just-- all of
the life ran out of me.

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:38.790
And then I realized, I
had this kind of insight.

00:52:38.790 --> 00:52:42.720
Wait a minute, that is
not going to serve here.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:46.950
And I reallocated my attention
to the sensation of my feet

00:52:46.950 --> 00:52:48.780
on the floor.

00:52:48.780 --> 00:52:51.000
I got myself grounded.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:56.700
And as I was grounding
myself, this sense

00:52:56.700 --> 00:53:01.170
of gratitude to the father
for bringing this little girl

00:53:01.170 --> 00:53:03.360
into the clinic arose.

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:07.860
I could feel my vascular
system warm up, become happier,

00:53:07.860 --> 00:53:09.240
if you will.

00:53:09.240 --> 00:53:11.760
And then I had this
sort of next wave

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:14.820
of just incredible
gratitude for the clinicians

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:17.190
who were serving this child.

00:53:17.190 --> 00:53:21.980
And that's compassion.

00:53:21.980 --> 00:53:26.810
Being in affective resonance
and somatic resonance

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:28.850
with the child was empathy.

00:53:28.850 --> 00:53:32.330
I would have been wiped
for all of the work

00:53:32.330 --> 00:53:37.110
that I've done in the medical
field as a support person.

00:53:37.110 --> 00:53:39.240
There's no way I
could've sustain it.

00:53:39.240 --> 00:53:42.950
But in fact, compassion
is characterized

00:53:42.950 --> 00:53:46.892
by unbiased resilience.

00:53:46.892 --> 00:53:47.550
